ValueDomain.preferredDefinition: The words or language units by which a thing is known.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance.

Concepts.definition: A sense organ needed for the detection of sound and for establishing balance. The outer ear consists of the auricle, the ear canal as well as the tympanic membrane. The middle ear is made up of an air-filled cavity behind the tympanic membrane that contains the ossicles (malleus, incus and stapes). The inner ear is made up of the cochlea needed for hearing and the vestibular apparatus required for balance.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.

Concepts.definition: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The paired caudal parts of the prosencephalon from which the THALAMUS, HYPOTHALAMUS, EPITHALAMUS, and SUBTHALAMUS are derived.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the forebrain that is located between the telencephalon and the brainstem; it is composed of the thalamus, hypothalamus, subthalamus, and epithalamus, which functions to help regulate many activities of the autonomic nervous system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The slender tubular part of the hypophysial diverticulum; the stalk of Rathke's pocket.

Concepts.definition: The slender tubular part of the hypophysial diverticulum; the stalk of Rathke's pocket.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A thin, transparent tissue divided into the palpebral conjunctiva (covering the inner side of the eye lid) and the bulbar conjunctiva (covering the eyeball).

Concepts.definition: A thin, transparent tissue divided into the palpebral conjunctiva (covering the inner side of the eye lid) and the bulbar conjunctiva (covering the eyeball).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Relating to the colon and rectum, or to the entire large bowel.

Concepts.definition: Relating to the colon and rectum, or to the entire large bowel.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

Concepts.definition: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain.

Concepts.definition: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction.

Concepts.definition: The anterior side of the thorax from the neck to the abdomen. The shape of the chest is often regarded as potential insight into a disease process, as in the case of barrel chest and respiratory dysfunction.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated definition with most recent NCIt version. mc 2/15/13

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the lymph nodes located in the neck.

Concepts.definition: Any of the lymph nodes located in the neck.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.

Concepts.definition: The part of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

Concepts.definition: The mucosal membranes located on the inside of the cheek, in the buccal cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tube through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels include a network of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

Concepts.definition: A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the ducts conveying bile between the liver and the intestine, including hepatic, cystic, and common bile duct.

Concepts.definition: Any of the ducts conveying bile between the liver and the intestine, including hepatic, cystic, and common bile duct.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.

Concepts.definition: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.

Concepts.definition: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated concept definition to use current NCIt. 6.4.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex).

Concepts.definition: A flattened, roughly triangular body resting upon the upper end of each kidney; it is one of the ductless glands furnishing internal secretions (epinephrine and norepinephrine from the medulla and steroid hormones from the cortex).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the body that lies between the thorax and the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The cavity located between the lungs and pelvis. It contains the lower esophagus, stomach, pancreas, intestines, liver, gallbladder and spleen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.

Concepts.definition: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outer part of the adrenal gland (a small organ on top of each kidney). The adrenal cortex makes androgen and corticosteroid hormones.

Concepts.definition: The outer region of the adrenal gland consisting of the zona glomerulosa, the zona fasciculata, and the zona reticularis. The adrenal cortex produces and secretes mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and adrenal androgens.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

Concepts.definition: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The dorsal area between the base of the neck and the sacrum.

Concepts.definition: The dorsal area between the base of the neck and the sacrum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.

Concepts.definition: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: That part of the central nervous system contained within the cranium, comprising the prosencephalon, mesencephalon, and rhombencephalon. It is derived from the anterior part of the embryonic neural tube. Functions include muscle control and coordination, sensory reception and integration, speech production, memory storage, and the elaboration of thought and emotions.

Concepts.definition: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that connects the cerebral hemispheres with the spinal cord. It consists of the mesencephalon, pons, and medulla oblongata.

Concepts.definition: Three sections, the midbrain, pons and medulla oblongata, that are located at the base of the brain. The brain stem regulates the central nervous system, and is vital as a conduit for motor and sensory innervations.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

Concepts.definition: One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

Concepts.definition: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

Concepts.definition: Either of the fleshy mounds in the rear pelvic area of the human body formed by the gluteal muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

Concepts.definition: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (sair-uh-BELL-um) The portion of the brain in the back of the head between the cerebrum and the brain stem. The cerebellum controls balance for walking and standing, and other complex motor functions.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the brain located at the base of the skull that is responsible for balance, equilibrium and movement.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

Concepts.definition: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

Concepts.definition: A gliding joint between the distal ends of the tibia and fibula and the proximal end of the talus.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: 09/10/2007 - Updated with NCI Thesaurus definition anc concept code.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Axilla; the hollow under the arm where it is joined to the shoulder.

Concepts.definition: The underside concavity where the arm and the shoulder are joined.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

Concepts.definition: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The area of the mouth under the ventral surface of the tongue.

Concepts.definition: The horseshoe-shaped part of the oral cavity bounded superiorly by the ventral surface of the tongue, inferiorly by the mylohyoid muscle, anterolaterally by the gingival surfaces of the mandible, and posteriorly by the anterior tonsillar pillar.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The cavity located at the upper end of the alimentary canal, behind the teeth and gums that is bounded on the outside by the lips, above by the hard and soft palates and below by the tongue.

Concepts.definition: The cavity located at the upper end of the alimentary canal, behind the teeth and gums that is bounded on the outside by the lips, above by the hard and soft palates and below by the tongue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear.

Concepts.definition: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone belonging to the middle part of the foot located between toes and ankle. There are 5 metatarsal bones and they are numbered from the medial side.

Concepts.definition: A bone belonging to the middle part of the foot located between toes and ankle. There are 5 metatarsal bones and they are numbered from the medial side.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any of the five bones between the wrist and the fingers that form the skeleton of the palm.

Concepts.definition: Any of the five bones between the wrist and the fingers that form the skeleton of the palm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The third division of the colon (large intestine). It communicates with the ascending colon in the upper right-hand quadrant of the abdomen and the descending colon in the upper left-hand quadrant.: A double layer of peritoneum that attaches to the back wall of the abdominal cavity and supports the small intestines.

Concepts.definition: The third division of the colon (large intestine). It communicates with the ascending colon in the upper right-hand quadrant of the abdomen and the descending colon in the upper left-hand quadrant.
A double layer of peritoneum that attaches to the back wall of the abdominal cavity and supports the small intestines.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The lower portion of the brainstem located between the pons and brainstem.  This structure contains several descending and ascending tracts, lower cranial nerve nuclei, a significant proportion of the reticular system of the brainstem and other structures.

Concepts.definition: The lower portion of the brainstem located between the pons and brainstem. This structure contains several descending and ascending tracts, lower cranial nerve nuclei, a significant proportion of the reticular system of the brainstem and other structures.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A group of organs surrounded by loose connective tissue, separating the two pleural sacs, between the sternum anteriorly and the vertebral column posteriorly as well as from the thoracic inlet superiorly to the diaphragm inferiorly. The mediastinum contains the heart and pericardium, the bases of the great vessels, the trachea and bronchi, esophagus, thymus, lymph nodes, thoracic duct, phrenic and vagus nerves, and other structures and tissues.

Concepts.definition: An anatomic site along the midline and under the sternum that contains the heart and pericardium, the bases of the great vessels, the trachea and bronchi, esophagus, thymus, lymph nodes, thoracic duct, phrenic and vagus nerves, and other structures and tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital.

Concepts.definition: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the three larger salivary glands including the parotid, submandibular and sublingual glands.

Concepts.definition: One of the three larger salivary glands including the parotid, submandibular and sublingual glands.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.: A lymph node which is located above the clavicle.

Concepts.definition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.
A lymph node which is located above the clavicle.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found throughout the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

Concepts.definition: A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found throughout the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Upper Lobe of the Lung

Concepts.definition: The lobe of the right lung that lies above the oblique and horizontal fissures and includes the apical, posterior and anterior bronchopulmonary segments; in the left lung, the lobe lies above the oblique fissure and contains the apicoposterior, anterior, superior lingular and inferior lingular segments.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The smallest lobe of the right lung, situated above the oblique fissure and below the horizontal fissure.

Concepts.longName: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung
Concepts.definition: The smallest lobe of the right lung, situated above the oblique fissure and below the horizontal fissure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The bottom most subdivision of either the right or left lung.

Concepts.definition: The bottom most subdivision of either the right or left lung.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: To become lower, grow less, or diminish, as in amount, intensity, degree, or value.: One of the two lower extremities in humans used for locomotion and support.

Concepts.definition: To become lower, grow less, or diminish, as in amount, intensity, degree, or value.
The portion of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole inferior limb.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The limb that is composed of the hip, thigh, leg and foot.

Concepts.definition: The limb that is composed of the hip, thigh, leg and foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: To become lower, grow less, or diminish, as in amount, intensity, degree, or value.: The dorsal area between the base of the neck and the sacrum.

Concepts.definition: To become lower, grow less, or diminish, as in amount, intensity, degree, or value.
The dorsal area between the base of the neck and the sacrum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The smaller lobe of the liver extending into the left side of the body.

Concepts.definition: The smaller lobe of the liver extending into the left side of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A small endocrine gland in the brain, situated beneath the back part of the corpus callosum, that secretes melatonin.

Concepts.definition: A small endocrine gland in the brain, situated beneath the back part of the corpus callosum, that secretes melatonin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The largest of the three paired salivary glands, located in front of the ear.

Concepts.definition: The largest of the three paired salivary glands, located in front of the ear.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the lobes of the cerebral hemisphere located superiorly to the occipital lobe and posteriorly to the frontal lobe. Cognition and visuospatial processing are its main functions.

Concepts.definition: One of the lobes of the cerebral hemisphere located superiorly to the occipital lobe and posteriorly to the frontal lobe. Cognition and visuospatial processing are its main functions.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Body regions near to the esophagus.: A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found throughout the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

Concepts.definition: Body regions near to the esophagus.

A bean-shaped organ surrounded by a connective tissue capsule. It is part of the lymphatic system and is found throughout the body. It is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and its main function is immune protection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The middle one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated and smooth types.

Concepts.definition: The middle one third of the esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated and smooth types.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The upper one third of esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated type.

Concepts.definition: The upper one third of esophagus in which the muscle layer is composed of muscle cells of the striated type.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: One of the four regions of cortex in each cerebral hemisphere. It is located posterior to the temporal lobe and inferior to the parietal lobe.

Concepts.definition: One of the four regions of cortex in each cerebral hemisphere. It is located posterior to the temporal lobe and inferior to the parietal lobe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A protective cover encircling a nerve, nerve fiber or axon.

Concepts.definition: A protective cover encircling a nerve, nerve fiber or axon.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The proximal portion of the respiratory passages on either side of the nasal septum lying between the floor of the cranium and the roof of the mouth and extending from the face to the pharynx. The nasal cavity is lined with ciliated mucosa, extending from the nares to the pharynx.

Concepts.definition: The proximal portion of the respiratory passages on either side of the nasal septum lying between the floor of the cranium and the roof of the mouth and extending from the face to the pharynx. The nasal cavity is lined with ciliated mucosa, extending from the nares to the pharynx.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The smooth muscle lining the uterus.

Concepts.definition: The smooth muscle lining the uterus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Mucous membrane.

Concepts.definition: Mucous membrane.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region that connects the head to the rest of the body.

Concepts.definition: The region that connects the head to the rest of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The pigmented projection on the surface of the breast. Ducts that conduct milk from the mammary glands to the surface of the breast exit through the nipple. (from MedTerms Medical Dictionary; medterms.com)

Concepts.definition: The pigmented protuberance on the surface of the breast through which milk is drawn from the breast.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.

Concepts.definition: A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The structure of the vertebrate skeleton supporting the lower limbs in humans and the hind limbs or corresponding parts in other vertebrates.

Concepts.definition: The bony, basin-shaped structure formed by the hipbones and the base of the backbone supporting the lower limbs in humans.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An external male reproductive organ. It contains a tube called the urethra, which carries semen and urine to the outside of the body.

Concepts.definition: The male organ of urination and copulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bone in the fingers or toes.

Concepts.definition: A bone in the fingers or toes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: (FAIR-inks) The hollow tube about 5 inches long that starts behind the nose and ends at the top of the trachea (windpipe) and esophagus (the tube that goes to the stomach).

Concepts.definition: A hollow tube that starts posterior to the mouth and nasal cavity and ends superior to the trachea and esophagus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

Concepts.definition: The tissue that lines the wall of the thoracic cavity and the surface of the lungs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The terminal portion of the gastrointestinal tract, extending from the rectosigmoid junction to the anal canal.

Concepts.definition: The terminal portion of the gastrointestinal tract, extending from the rectosigmoid junction to the anal canal.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A light-sensitive membrane that lines the back wall of the eyeball. The retina is continuous with the optic nerve and this way transmits optical images to the brain.

Concepts.definition: A light-sensitive membrane that lines the back wall of the eyeball. The retina is continuous with the optic nerve and this way transmits optical images to the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The back of the abdomen where the kidneys lie and the great blood vessels run.

Concepts.definition: The back of the abdomen where the kidneys lie and the great blood vessels run.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any one of the paired bones, 12 on either side, extending from the thoracic vertebrae toward the median line on the ventral aspect of the trunk. The long curved bones which form the rib cage. Generally, ribs 1 to 7 are connected to the sternum' by their costal cartilages and are called true ribs, whereas ribs 8 to 12 are termed false ribs.

Concepts.definition: Any one of the paired bones, 12 on either side, extending from the thoracic vertebrae toward the median line on the ventral aspect of the trunk. The long curved bones which form the rib cage. Generally, ribs 1 to 7 are connected to the sternum by their costal cartilages and are called true ribs, whereas ribs 8 to 12 are termed false ribs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An endocrine gland located at the base of the neck that produces and secretes thyroxine and other hormones. Thyroxine is important for metabolic control.

Concepts.definition: An endocrine gland located at the base of the neck that produces and secretes thyroxine and other hormones. Thyroxine is important for metabolic control.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones.

Concepts.definition: Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Lower lateral part of the cerebral hemisphere.

Concepts.definition: One of the cerebral lobes. It is located inferior to the frontal and parietal lobes and anterior to the occipital lobe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Striated muscles are appendicular and axial muscles typically connected at either or both ends to the bony skeleton of the body.  Striated muscle fibers contain a highly organized, contractile cytoskeletal apparatus with a striated microscopic appearance; muscle contraction is typically under voluntary control.

Concepts.definition: Striated muscles are appendicular and axial muscles typically connected at either or both ends to the bony skeleton of the body.  Striated muscle fibers contain a highly organized, contractile cytoskeletal apparatus with a striated microscopic appearance; muscle contraction is typically under voluntary control.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.

Concepts.definition: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The undersurface of the foot.

Concepts.definition: The undersurface of the foot.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. It is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. The smooth muscle cells contain a contractile apparatus composed of thin and thick filaments and a cytoskeleton composed of intermediate filaments.

Concepts.definition: Involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. It is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. The smooth muscle cells contain a contractile apparatus composed of thin and thick filaments and a cytoskeleton composed of intermediate filaments.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The section of the intestines between the pylorus and cecum. The small intestine is approximately 20 feet long and consists of the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum. Its main function is to absorb nutrients from food as the food is transported to the large intestine.

Concepts.definition: The section of the intestines between the pylorus and cecum. The small intestine is approximately 20 feet long and consists of the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum. Its main function is to absorb nutrients from food as the food is transported to the large intestine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: No Value Exists

Concepts.definition: The area of the head comprised of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The region of the body between the neck and the upper arm.

Concepts.definition: The region of the body between the neck and the upper arm.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The ureter connecting the right kidney to the bladder.

Concepts.definition: The ureter connecting the right kidney to the bladder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The ovary that is located in the right side of the pelvis.

Concepts.definition: The ovary that is located in the right side of the pelvis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.: Posterior part of the cerebral hemisphere.

Concepts.definition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.
One of the four regions of cortex in each cerebral hemisphere. It is located posterior to the temporal lobe and inferior to the parietal lobe.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The 3-lobed lung located on the right side of the body. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: The 3-lobed lung located on the right side of the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus. (NCI)

Concepts.definition: Being or located on or directed toward the side of the body to the east when facing north.
A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bean-shaped retroperitoneal organ situated below the diaphragm and posterior to the liver.
